  B(i, j) = A(30 – j, 40 – i)

for 1 ≤ i ≤ 39 and 1 ≤ j ≤ 29. This is the final answer. (Any listing of the 1131 individual numbers is equivalent to the matrix defined by the above transformation.)</answer>

In other words, if you call the original 40×39 matrix A (with row indices 0…39 and column indices 0…38), then the final matrix H (with 39 rows and 40 columns) is given entry‐by‐entry by

  H[i,j] = { 0  if A[j,i] is divisible by 3 
       A[j,i] otherwise }

for i = 0,…,38 and j = 0,…,39. This matrix is exactly the result after performing, in order, the identity transformation, two successive diagonal mirroring (which cancel), a vertical mirroring, “zero‐ing” all multiples of 3, a 180° rotation, another diagonal mirroring, and a final vertical mirroring.
